			<div type="month" mhs:startingPage="315"  mhs:precedingFile="" mhs:followingFile="JQADiaries-v24-1801-02-p317.xml" mhs:volume="24">
				<bibl n="metadata"><date from="1801-01-01" to="1801-01-31"/></bibl>

				<!--D/JQA/24.2336-->
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-01-01">
					<head>1 January 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-01-01"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					<subject>Recreation</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<pb n="315"/>
						<dateline><hi rend="italic">January 1801.</hi></dateline>
						<p><date>1. </date>Took a walk in the park— Went in the evening to the play
							at <persRef ref="cohen-ephraim">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi>
								Cohen’s</persRef>— The performances were Eugenie, and Les Vendanges
							de Suresne— Called afterwards at <persRef ref="proby-john">Lord
								Carysfort’s</persRef>, where <persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine"
									>M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi> A</persRef>. had pass’d the Evening—
								<persRef ref="u">Miss Bisschofwerder</persRef> was there
							likewise.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-01-02">
					<head>2 January 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-01-02"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					<subject>Recreation</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>2. </date>A ball this evening at <persRef ref="brown-charles">D<hi
									rend="superscript">r:</hi> Brown’s</persRef>— Danced a couple of dances—
							Play’d chess, the remainder of the evening, with <hi
								rend="strikethrough">M</hi><hi rend="superscript strikethrough">r:</hi><hi
								rend="strikethrough"> Kinnaird, and with lor</hi> D<hi rend="superscript"
								>r:</hi> Brown.— We came home between 11 and 12.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-01-03">
					<head>3 January 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-01-03"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					<subject>Recreation</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>3. </date>Evening party at the <persRef ref="u">Baron de
								Hagen’s</persRef>— Play’d chess with <persRef ref="vonbruhl-karl"
								>Count Brühl</persRef>, and with <persRef ref="u">M<hi rend="superscript"
									>r:</hi> Landon</persRef>. <persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine"
									>M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi> A</persRef>. spent the Evening at
								<persRef ref="proby-elizabeth">Lady Carysfort’s</persRef>.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-01-04">
					<head>4 January 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-01-04"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					<subject>Recreation</subject>
						<subject>Court Life and Society (European)</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>4. </date>Read as usual a sermon of <persRef ref="tillotson-john"
								>Tillotson</persRef>— Dined at <persRef ref="brown-charles">D<hi
									rend="superscript">r:</hi> Brown’s</persRef>— <persRef
								ref="cohen-ephraim">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi> Cohen</persRef> and
								<persRef ref="cohen-pessel;u">his family</persRef> there. At Court
							in the evening.— <persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript"
									>rs:</hi> A</persRef>— did not go, and proposes not to go again
							this winter— Play’d whist with <persRef ref="u">Madame de
								Heinitz</persRef> and <persRef ref="u">Miss Hagen</persRef>—
							Return’d to D<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi> Brown’s— <persRef ref="u"
								>Caulfield</persRef> there; and sung a number of fine songs.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-01-05">
					<head>5 January 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-01-05"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>5. </date>Miss Brown call’d for half an hour this afternoon— Visit
							from <persRef ref="fagel-robert">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi>
							Fagel</persRef>— Reading <persRef ref="moore-john">D<hi rend="superscript"
									>r:</hi> Moore’s</persRef> Mordaunt which I find very
							amusing.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-01-06">
					<head>6 January 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-01-06"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					<subject>Recreation</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>6. </date>We had a company of about thirty persons this evening to
							a little dance and supper— Chiefly consisting of the English now here— I
							danced almost the whole evening— It was two in the morning before we
							broke up. <persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi>
								A</persRef>— was too much fatigued.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-01-07">
					<head>7 January 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-01-07"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>7. </date>The weather is so moderate and the streets so bad that I
							can scarcely walk at all— <persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi
									rend="superscript">rs:</hi> A</persRef>— though quite unwell went in the
							Evening to <persRef ref="stgeorge-melesina">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi>
									S<hi rend="superscript">t:</hi> George’s</persRef>— <persRef ref="u"
									>M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi> Stamford</persRef>— <persRef
								ref="proby-elizabeth">Lady Carysfort</persRef>, <persRef ref="u"
								>Miss Bischofwerder</persRef> &amp;c there— We gave them lessons of
							reversi.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-01-08">
					<head>8 January 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-01-08"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					<subject>Health and Illness</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>8. </date><persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript"
									>rs:</hi> A</persRef>— was extremely ill, all night and this
							morning— Recovered somewhat in the forenoon. I dined with the Hanoverian
							Minister the <persRef ref="reden-friedrich">Count de Reden</persRef>— A
							company of fourteen persons— Partly diplomatic— Evening at home, reading
							Mordaunt to M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi> A. who was much better.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-01-09">
					<head>9 January 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-01-09"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					<subject>Health and Illness</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>9. </date><persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript"
									>rs:</hi> A</persRef>— continues weak and unwell— Hope will
							intrude upon the slightest occasion and catch at every straw. I have
							every reason for excluding it, and receive perpetual warnings against
							its indulgence. I was for about half an hour this evening at <persRef
								ref="augustusferdinand">Prince Ferdinand’s</persRef>— Spent the
							remainder at home. At Prince Ferdinand’s I saw the <persRef
								ref="tilly-alexandre">Count Tilli</persRef> who married <persRef
								ref="bingham-william">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi> Bingham’s</persRef>
							<persRef ref="tilly-maria">daughter</persRef>.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-01-10">
					<head>10 January 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-01-10"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>10. </date>Weather becoming cold— We changed our dining apartment—
							I write as much as I can, but slide insensibly into laziness. Very short
							walk under the trees before dinner— Finish’d reading Mordaunt in the
							evening.— Party at <persRef ref="vonrochow-friedrich">M<hi rend="superscript"
									>r:</hi> Rochow’s</persRef>, which I should have attended, but
							did not— Invitation forgotten by <persRef ref="whitcomb-tilly">my
								servant</persRef>.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-01-11">
					<head>11 January 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-01-11"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					<subject>Court Life and Society (European)</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>11. </date>Took a walk in the park this forenoon. The first time
							for many days— Miss Brown called here before dinner— <persRef
								ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi> A.</persRef>
							spent an hour this evening with <persRef ref="proby-elizabeth">Lady
								Carysfort</persRef>.— I was at Court—at the palace, the ladies in
							hoops— The carnival commences with this— Came home early— Letters from
								<persRef ref="king-rufus">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi> King</persRef>.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-01-12">
					<head>12 January 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-01-12"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					<subject>Recreation</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>12. </date>Wrote to <persRef ref="king-rufus">M<hi rend="superscript"
									>r:</hi> King</persRef>— Went to the Opera this evening— Vasco
							da Gama— <persRef ref="himmel-friedrich">Himmel’s</persRef> music— So
							bad, that I could not stay above half the performance through— Spent the
							remainder of the Evening at <persRef ref="brown-charles">D<hi rend="superscript"
									>r:</hi> Brown’s</persRef>, where <persRef
								ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi> A</persRef>—
							was— She had been unwell there— <persRef ref="hunter-elizabeth">M<hi
									rend="superscript">rs:</hi> Hunter</persRef> call’d upon her this
							forenoon.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-01-13">
					<head>13 January 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-01-13"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					<subject>Recreation</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>13. </date><persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript"
									>rs:</hi> A.</persRef> was very unwell this afternoon, but spent
							the Evening with <persRef ref="proby-elizabeth">Lady
							Carysfort</persRef>— I pass’d it at <persRef
								ref="schulenburgkehnert-frederick">Count Schulenburg’s</persRef>;
							but did not go to the redoute— Play’d chess with <persRef
								ref="vonbruhl-karl">Count Brühl</persRef>— Busy the forenoon in
							writing to <persRef ref="murray-william2">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi>
								Murray</persRef>.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-01-14">
					<head>14 January 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-01-14"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					<subject>Recreation</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<pb n="316" type="ms"/>
						<p><date>14. </date>Went this forenoon with <persRef
								ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi> A</persRef>—
							to look at a lodging— Found it not large enough.— Short walk. Read part
							of <persRef ref="moliere">Moliere’s</persRef> Amphytrion to M<hi
								rend="superscript">rs:</hi> A— Evening at <persRef ref="brown-charles">D<hi
									rend="superscript">r:</hi> Brown’s</persRef>— Play’d chess with him
							untill 11. o’clock.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-01-15">
					<head>15 January 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-01-15"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>15. </date>Excepting a morning walk, at home the whole day.
								<persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi>
								A</persRef>— was very ill for about an hour in the afternoon—
								<persRef ref="stgeorge-melesina">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi> S<hi
									rend="superscript">t:</hi> George</persRef> called for half an hour this
							evening.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-01-16">
					<head>16 January 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-01-16"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					<subject>Health and Illness</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>16. </date>Spent a couple of hours this forenoon in reading, at the
							Casino— Then a short walk— <persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi
									rend="superscript">rs:</hi> A.</persRef> who had had a bad night was
							excessively ill again this afternoon— These illnesses come with such
							great and daily increasing violence that they cannot much longer
							continue.— At home with her, all the Evening.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-01-17">
					<head>17 January 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-01-17"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>17. </date>I confine myself almost entirely to the house, on
								<persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi>
								A’s</persRef>— account— She was again very ill this afternoon;
							though not quite so bad as yesterday.— The two eldest Miss Brown’s spent
							the Evening with her—</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-01-18">
					<head>18 January 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-01-18"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					<subject>Health and Illness</subject>
						<subject>Court Life and Society (European)</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>18. </date>There was a ball at Court this Evening— But the <persRef
								ref="frederick-william-iii">king</persRef> and <persRef
								ref="louiseauguste">queen</persRef> being both unwell, neither were
							present at it, and I did not go. <persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine"
									>M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi> A</persRef>— remains extremely
							feeble.— This afternoon however we was not so ill, as she has been many
							days past.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-01-19">
					<head>19 January 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-01-19"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					<subject>Recreation</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>19. </date><persRef ref="vonbruhl-karl;vonbruhl-sophia">Count and
								Countess Brühl</persRef>, and <persRef ref="bruhl-maria">their
									daughter Mary</persRef> call’d this afternoon to see <persRef
								ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi> A</persRef>— I
							pass’d the evening at <persRef ref="augustusferdinand">Prince
								Ferdinand’s</persRef>, where I accompanied them— Play’d Casino, with
							the prince, princess <persRef ref="u">Dolgorouky</persRef> and Countess
							Brühl— They took me home with them.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-01-20">
					<head>20 January 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-01-20"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					<subject>Recreation</subject>
						<subject>Court Life and Society (European)</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>20. </date>Ball this evening at the <persRef ref="vonvoss-otto"
								>Minister Voss’s</persRef>— The <persRef ref="frederick-william-iii"
								>king</persRef> and <persRef ref="louiseauguste">queen</persRef>
							were not there— Saw the <persRef ref="charlotte-georgine">Duchess of
								Saxe Hildburgshausen</persRef>, the queen’s sister— Stay’d there a
							very short time and went from thence to <persRef ref="u">M<hi rend="superscript"
									>r:</hi> Schickler’s</persRef>, where there was a very large
							party— Play’d Boston with <persRef ref="divova-elisaveta">Madame
								Divoff</persRef>, <persRef ref="u">Madame Strickhuysen</persRef> and
								<persRef ref="u">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi> Aubry</persRef>, a
							secretary of the Russian legation— The Opera’s and Redoute’s have been
							suspended owing to the illness of the king and queen.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-01-21">
					<head>21 January 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-01-21"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					<subject>Health and Illness</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>21. </date>Stormy weather— In the midst of a squall this forenoon,
							with a flight of snow there was a heavy clap of thunder— <persRef
								ref="u">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi> Ribke</persRef> called in the
							morning— <persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi>
								A</persRef>— very unwell the whole day— After dinner extremely ill—
							Rather better however towards evening— Read to her, Castle-Rackrent; and
							a canto of <persRef ref="butler-samuel3">Butler’s</persRef>
							Hudibras.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-01-22">
					<head>22 January 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-01-22"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					<subject>Health and Illness</subject>
						<subject>Recreation</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>22. </date><persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript"
									>rs:</hi> A</persRef>— much better again all this day. I believe
							the alternation perpetually renewed of hope and disappointment is one of
							the greatest miseries that can be inflicted upon human beings— <persRef
								ref="brown-mary">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi> Brown</persRef> and
								<persRef ref="brown-isabella">Bell</persRef>, and <persRef ref="u"
								>Miss Bisschoffwerder</persRef> spent the evening with M<hi
								rend="superscript">rs:</hi> A— I call’d this forenoon at the Casino—spent
							the evening at <persRef ref="massow-julius">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi>
								Massow’s</persRef>— Play’d whist with <persRef ref="u">Countess
								Keyserling</persRef>, the <persRef ref="vonschrotter-friedrich"
								>Minister Schrötter</persRef>, and <persRef
								ref="u">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi>
								Knoblauch</persRef>— Did not stay to supper.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-01-23">
					<head>23 January 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-01-23"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>23. </date><persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript"
									>rs:</hi> A</persRef>— again very unwell— I was an hour this
							forenoon at the Casino— Walk’d with <persRef ref="garlike-benjamin">M<hi
									rend="superscript">r:</hi> Garlike</persRef> under the Linden— Read
							Hudibras in the Evening to M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi> A.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-01-24">
					<head>24 January 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-01-24"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					<subject>Recreation</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>24. </date><persRef key="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi> A</persRef>— had a tolerably good day—
							Was at the Assembly this evening at <persRef ref="vonheinitz-friedrich">Baron Heinitz’s</persRef>. Play’d Whist with
								<persRef ref="u">Madame de Saldern</persRef>, M<hi rend="superscript"
								>r:</hi> Heinitz, and <persRef ref="u">Colonel Hardenberg</persRef>—
							Read Hudibras.— Was at <persRef ref="u">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi>
								Schickler’s</persRef> compting house this morning.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-01-25">
					<head>25 January 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-01-25"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>25. </date><persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript"
									>rs:</hi> A</persRef>— very ill all the first part of the day,
							and untill five or six o’clock in the evening. Afterwards much better—
							There was no Court this Evening.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-01-26">
					<head>26 January 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-01-26"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>26. </date><persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript"
									>rs:</hi> A</persRef>— Had a pretty good day again— Snowy day—
							Second performance of the first Opera this evening, but I did not attend
							it— Read Hudibras to M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi> A.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-01-27">
					<head>27 January 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-01-27"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					<subject>Recreation</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>27. </date><persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript"
									>rs:</hi> A</persRef>: had one more day of respite— Miss Brown
							spent the Evening with her— I was at the <persRef
								ref="vonschrotter-friedrich">Minister Schrötter’s</persRef>— A
							redoute party, and supper; to which I did not stay— Play’d whist with
								<persRef ref="vonderreck-elise">Madame de Reck</persRef>, <persRef
								ref="munchhausen-berhardine">Madame de Münchhausen</persRef>, and
								<persRef ref="vondonhoff-august">Count Dönhoff</persRef>.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-01-28">
					<head>28 January 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-01-28"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<pb n="317" type="ms"/>
						<p><date>28. </date><persRef ref="proby-elizabeth"
								>Lady Carysfort</persRef> called on <persRef
								ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi> A</persRef>—
							this forenoon— Weather so bad I could not walk out— By a sore throat
							prevented from reading loud, this evening; only the close of a canto of
							Hudibras.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-01-29">
					<head>29 January 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-01-29"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					<subject>Court Life and Society (European)</subject>
						<subject>Recreation</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>29. </date>The hereditary <persRef ref="elena-pavlovna">princess of
								Mecklenburg Schwerin</persRef>, a daughter of the <persRef
								ref="paul-i">Emperor of Russia</persRef>, spends the rest of the
							carnival here— A court of presentation was held at the palace, where she
							lodges, this afternoon, at half past five— I went— Large ball at
								<persRef ref="proby-john">Lord Carysfort’s</persRef>— I play’d chess
							with <persRef ref="vonbruhl-karl">Count Brühl</persRef>— Came home soon
							after nine, and found <persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi
									rend="superscript">rs:</hi> A</persRef>— very ill— She continued so
							almost the whole night.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-01-30">
					<head>30 January 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-01-30"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>30. </date>After a very stormy night, this day has been cold—
								<persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi>
								A</persRef>— continued unwell, though towards evening some what
							better— Walk’d before dinner; but did not go to the Opera this Evening.
							Finished reading Hudibras to M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi> A— and read
							likewise some of <persRef ref="chatterton-thomas">Chatterton’s</persRef>
							poems.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-01-31">
					<head>31 January 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-01-31"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					<subject>Recreation</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>31. </date>Rain all the morning— Hard frost towards night— Stormy—
								<persRef ref="u">Miss Bischoffwerder</persRef> &amp; the <persRef
								ref="brown-fanny;brown-isabella;brown-margaret">Miss
								Brown’s</persRef> spent the Evening with <persRef
								ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi> A</persRef>— I
							was at the Assembly at <persRef ref="podewils-friedrich">Count
								Podewils’s</persRef>— Play’d whist with <persRef
								ref="vonderreck-elise">Madame de Reck</persRef>, <persRef ref="u"
									>M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi> Wulcknitz</persRef> and another
							gentleman— The <persRef ref="frederick-william-iii">king</persRef> and
								<persRef ref="elena-pavlovna">princess of Mecklenburg</persRef> were
							there.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-01-xx">
					<head>Day</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-01"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date><hi rend="italic">Day</hi>—</date> Rise between 8 and 9. Seldom earlier; for
							which a partial apology arises from the very frequent bad nights
								<persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine">my wife’s</persRef> state of
							health occasions— Revise my translation of Oberon, about half an hour.
							Breakfast; dress— Read or write till 2. Walk an hour— Dine— Spend the
							evening abroad, or reading to M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi> A— more
							frequently the latter, untill about 10— Take a light supper— Bed at
							11.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>
